     "text": [
      "The concept of gravity has been understood and described by various scientists and philosophers throughout history. While it's difficult to attribute the \"discovery\" of gravity to a single person, I can give you some insight into the key figures who contributed to our understanding of gravity.\n",
      "\n",
      "The ancient Greek philosopher Aristotle (384-322 BCE) was one of the first to describe the concept of gravity, although he didn't use that term. He believed that objects tend to move towards their natural place, with heavier objects moving towards the center of the Earth.\n",
      "\n",
      "However, the most famous and influential figure in the history of gravity is Sir Isaac Newton (1643-1727). Newton's groundbreaking work, \"Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica\" (Mathematical Principles of Natural Philosophy), published in 1687, laid the foundation for our modern understanding of gravity. He formulated the law of universal gravitation, which states that every point mass attracts every other point mass by a force acting along the line intersecting both points.\n",
      "\n",
      "Newton's law of gravity, often referred to as the \"law of universal gravitation,\" describes the gravitational force between two objects as a function of their masses and the distance between them. This fundamental concept has had a profound impact on our understanding of the natural world, from the motion of planets to the behavior of subatomic particles.\n",
      "\n",
      "So, while it's not possible to identify a single \"first person\" to discover gravity, Sir Isaac Newton is widely recognized as the scientist who developed the most comprehensive and influential theory of gravity, which has shaped our understanding of the universe for centuries.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
